    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-18T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-18T11:00:00-05:00" n="934"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d934">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 E.W./9–1844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ireland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dublin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-18T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 18, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>148. Last night I received your No. 175<note n="42" xml:id="d934fn42">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                    </note> and your circular telegram of September 16<note n="43" xml:id="d934fn43">
                        <ref target="frus1944v02#pg_231">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            231</ref>.</note> this morning, asking us to hold up action on Bretton
                    Woods declaration until after consultation with London. In conformity with this
                    line of action, I conferred this morning with Sir John Maffey<note n="44"
                        xml:id="d934fn44">Sir John Maffey, British Representative in Ireland.</note>
                    regarding your 175, containing instructions as to German war criminals. He has
                    not been advised of our proposed <hi rend="italic">démarche</hi> to Irish
                    Government on Nazi fugitives. His personal view was that in the interests of
                    United Nations solidarity and Britain’s peculiar interests here it would be
                    desirable to make joint representations. We [<hi rend="italic">He?</hi>]
                    unreservedly favored the proposal but asked for a brief period in which to
                    consult this [<hi rend="italic">his?</hi>] Government. I told him that I would
                    inform you and recommend joint action if British Government was prepared to
                    reach decision without undue delay. I also told him that I thought it probable
                    that British Government had already been consulted and advised. Am therefore not
                    communicating with External Affairs until hear further from you.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
